[ProMED thanks Mahmoud Orabi for these reports on Crimean-Congo hemorrhagic fever (CCHF) cases reported in Mauritania.

The 1st case was reported last week (https://nouakchot.com/article/24753; in Arabic) and the reports above indicate that the 2 cases are from the same area in the interior of the country.

Most known human cases of CCHF in West Africa have been reported from southern Mauritania. The 1st case was documented in 1983(1) in a camel and cattle breeder in Selibaby, Guidimakha region, possibly related to close contact with infected camels or cattle.

Subsequent reports of cases were from the Trarza region with possible involvement of sheep as a source of transmission to humans(2). In 2003, a major outbreak was reported, involving 35 persons in Nouakchott, along with secondary infections among hospital staff, and sporadic reports from Brakna and Hodh Elgharbi regions(3).

In 2015, a study on hemorrhagic fever during a Rift Valley fever outbreak in Mauritania showed that 6/184 (3.3%) samples, mostly from the southern part of the country, were positive for CCHF viral RNA(4). Animal studies also have demonstrated a high seroprevalence in cattle in Mauritania.

Most cases of CCHF in this region have been reported during the long dry season (December-July)(5).

The recent reports highlight that CCHF is both enzootic and endemic in Mauritania and that there is a need for better diagnostic capacity, increased awareness, and knowledge of the epidemiology of CCHF among health providers, and regional surveillance using a One Health approach.

References
----------
1. Saluzzo JF, Camicas JL, Chartier C, et al. Crimean-Congo haemorrhagic fever (CCHF) virus in Mauritania [in French]. Cah. ORSTOM, Sér. Entomolog. Méd. Parasitolog. 1986; 24: 129-37.
2. Gonzalez JP, LeGuenno B, Guillaud M, Wilson ML. A fatal case of Crimean-Congo haemorrhagic fever in Mauritania: virological and serological evidence suggesting epidemic transmission. Trans R Soc Trop Med Hyg. 1990; 84(4):573-6; https://doi.org/10.1016/0035-9203(90)90045-g.
3. Nabeth P, Cheikh DO, Lo B, et al. Crimean-Congo hemorrhagic fever, Mauritania. Emerg Infect Dis. 2004; 10(12): 2143-9; https://doi.org/10.3201/eid1012.040535.
4. Bob NS, Bâ H, Fall G, et al. Detection of the Northeastern African Rift Valley fever virus lineage during the 2015 outbreak in Mauritania. Open Forum Infect Dis. 2017; 4(2):ofx087; https://doi.org/10.1093/ofid/ofx087
5. Boushab BM, Kelly M, Kébé H, et al. Crimean-Congo hemorrhagic fever, Mauritania. Emerg Infect Dis. 2020; 26(4): 817-818; https://doi.org/10.3201/eid2604.191292.

